  "texts": [
    "In more explicit way, if we have an under determined linear differential operator of order k, say A, then for the equation A u = f, we may find a sequence f i bounded in L 1 for which any sequence of solutions u i must satisfy∥∇ k u i ∥ L 1 → ∞.In elasticity theory, this is of interest when A is the symmetric part of the gradient (cf.",
    "Korn's inequality [27] asserting instead that for p ∈ (1, ∞) a regularity gain can be expected for the symmetric part of the gradient).",
    "In the theory of currents, it is useful to consider A = d, the exterior derivative.",
    "Except for the case when d coincides with the Frechét derivative, the operator is indeed under determined.The non-inequality of Ornstein can be dualised to obtain an analogous result near L ∞.",
    "It appears that the first instance of an L ∞ result is due to De Leeuw and Mirkil [17] (in French) and came before Ornstein's result."
  ],
